=== PR #261 ===
{"body":"The comment “# All tests” on the Nx command is misleading: `npx nx run-many --target=test --all` will only run Nx-inferred `test` targets (e.g., Jest), and does not run the .NET test projects. Consider rewording the comment to clarify what it covers (e.g., “All Nx/Jest tests”) or adjusting the documented command if the intent is truly to run everything.\n","line":82,"path":"README.md"}
{"body":"`dotnet test` will also execute the integration test project in the solution, which uses Testcontainers (PostgreSQL/Redis) and therefore requires a working Docker engine. Consider noting this requirement (or documenting a way to run only unit tests) so the command “works as documented” for readers without Docker.\n","line":84,"path":"README.md"}
=== PR #262 ===
{"body":"docker-compose uses the liveness endpoint (/health/live) as the service healthcheck. Because `web` depends on `api` being `service_healthy`, this can mark the API healthy even if DB/Redis connectivity is broken (liveness intentionally skips external dependencies). Consider switching the compose healthcheck to `/health/ready` (or update the orchestration expectations accordingly).\n","line":73,"path":"docker/docker-compose.yml"}
{"body":"The Dockerfile HEALTHCHECK relies on `curl` being present in the runtime image, but this Dockerfile doesn’t install it. To avoid fragile dependence on what the base image happens to include, explicitly install `curl` (and CA certs) in the runtime stage or use an alternative probe mechanism that’s guaranteed to exist.","line":44,"path":"docker/api.Dockerfile"}
{"body":"The comment says the compose file can override the Docker liveness check for readiness, but docker-compose.yml is currently also using `/health/live`. Either update the compose healthcheck to `/health/ready` or adjust this comment so it matches the actual configuration.\n","line":41,"path":"docker/api.Dockerfile"}
{"body":"This section explains migrations are automatic, but the later \"Health Checks\" section still documents the API Docker healthcheck endpoint as `/health` even though the compose/Dockerfile healthcheck is now `/health/live`. Please update the README healthcheck documentation to match the new endpoint to avoid confusion during troubleshooting.","line":116,"path":"docker/README.md"}
{"body":"CLAUDE.md still describes the project/prerequisites as .NET 9, but the API projects target `net10.0` and the Dockerfile uses `mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/*:10.0`. Since this file is being updated, please align the .NET version references in the header/Tech Stack/Prerequisites to avoid misleading setup instructions.","line":49,"path":"CLAUDE.md"}
=== PR #263 ===
{"body":"`UpdatedById` is optional (defaults to `Guid.Empty`) and the handler only publishes `TicketUpdatedEvent` when it’s provided. Since status changes are part of the email-notification lifecycle, consider making this parameter required (no default) and validating it’s non-empty so updates can’t silently skip publishing.","line":11,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/UpdateStatus/UpdateTicketStatusHandler.cs"}
{"body":"`TicketUpdatedEvent.UpdatedAt` is set with a fresh `DateTime.UtcNow`, which can differ from the persisted `ticket.UpdatedAt` (especially since `ApplicationDbContext.SaveChanges*` overwrites timestamps). Prefer populating the event timestamp from the entity after `SaveChangesAsync` so event data matches the stored record.\n","line":96,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/UpdateStatus/UpdateTicketStatusHandler.cs"}
{"body":"This loads the assigned user as a full tracked entity, even though only name/email are used for the event. Prefer projecting just the needed fields (like the other user lookups) to reduce query cost and avoid pulling unnecessary columns into the change tracker.","line":76,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/UpdateStatus/UpdateTicketStatusHandler.cs"}
{"body":"Publishing occurs after the DB write and cache invalidation; if `_publishEndpoint.Publish` throws, the API will return an error even though the status change is already committed (and caches were cleared). Consider handling publish failures (e.g., try/catch + logging) or using an outbox pattern so notification failures don’t surface as failed commands.","line":83,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/UpdateStatus/UpdateTicketStatusHandler.cs"}
{"body":"Publishing the event after `SaveChangesAsync` can cause the handler to throw (and the API to return an error) even though the assignment is already persisted if the message bus is unavailable. Consider handling publish exceptions or adopting an outbox so the command result reflects the actual persisted state.","line":81,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/Assign/AssignTicketHandler.cs"}
{"body":"`ReassignedById` defaults to `Guid.Empty` and publishing is conditional. Since reassignments are part of the notification workflow, make the actor ID required (and validate non-empty) to avoid silent non-publishing when a caller forgets to pass it.","line":10,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/Reassign/ReassignTicketHandler.cs"}
{"body":"As with other handlers, publishing after the DB write means a publish failure can bubble up after the ticket is already reassigned, returning an error to the caller for a successful persistence operation. Consider catching publish exceptions/logging or using an outbox to decouple persistence from notification delivery.","line":83,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Tickets/Reassign/ReassignTicketHandler.cs"}
{"body":"The submitter projection includes `u.Id`, but that value isn’t used anywhere in the handler/event payload. Dropping unused selected fields keeps queries minimal and avoids misleading future readers about required data.\n","line":64,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Comments/Create/AddCommentHandler.cs"}
{"body":"If publishing the `CommentAddedEvent` fails, this handler will throw after the comment is already saved, causing clients to see an error for a successfully persisted comment. Consider handling publish failures (log + continue) or using an outbox pattern to avoid inconsistent outcomes.","line":78,"path":"apps/api/src/Features/Comments/Create/AddCommentHandler.cs"}
{"body":"These tests now inject `MockPublishEndpoint`, but they don’t assert that a `TicketUpdatedEvent` is published (and they create the command without `UpdatedById`, so the publish path isn’t exercised). Add an assertion against the mock’s captured messages and pass a non-empty `UpdatedById` so the new notification behavior is covered.","line":25,"path":"apps/api/Hickory.Api.Tests/Features/Tickets/UpdateTicketStatusHandlerTests.cs"}
{"body":"The handler now publishes `TicketAssignedEvent`, but the tests don’t assert that the event was published or validate its key fields. Capture the `MockPublishEndpoint` instance and add assertions on `PublishedMessages` so the notification wiring is actually tested.","line":34,"path":"apps/api/Hickory.Api.Tests/Features/Tickets/AssignTicketHandlerTests.cs"}
{"body":"`ConnectPublishObserver` currently throws `NotImplementedException`. Since this class is meant to be a reusable test double for `IPublishEndpoint`, it should behave as a safe no-op for all interface methods (e.g., return a dummy `ConnectHandle`) to avoid surprising failures if a test or library code starts using observers.\n","line":15,"path":"apps/api/Hickory.Api.Tests/TestUtilities/MockPublishEndpoint.cs"}

